item_A: Parties: Two education-research organizations (plaintiffs) sued the U.S. Department of Education and its Secretary (defendants).

Background statutory framework: ESRA tasks the Department, via IES and its Centers, with conducting, assessing, collecting, and disseminating education research to improve the quantity and quality of educational data.
Executive Order 14,242 (Mar. 20, 2025) directed the Secretary to take steps, to the extent permitted by law, to facilitate closure of the Department of Education.
Agency actions: The Department canceled most IES contracts used to collect/analyze/publish educational data and announced a nearly 50% Reduction in Force.
Filing: Plaintiffs filed suit on April 24, 2025, in the U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia.

Plaintiffs’ alleged harm: Limitation of availability and access to significant education datasets and interference with IES’s ability to fulfill its ESRA-mandated data collection and dissemination functions.

Claims: APA violations (exceeded statutory authority, not in accordance with law, arbitrary and capricious) and constitutional separation-of-powers violations; also alleged actions exceeded authority under ESRA.

Relief sought: Declaratory judgment of APA violations; injunction preventing refusal to fulfill contracts or destruction of existing datasets; orders to reinstate canceled contracts and restore sufficient workforce to enable IES duties.
Assignment: The case was assigned to District Judge Trevor N. McFadden.
Preliminary injunction request: Filed May 2; plaintiffs asserted irreparable harm tied to the President’s directives.

Stay motion: Defendants sought a stay based on a related case; the court denied the stay (May 6), finding litigation hardship insufficient and no comity concerns since both matters were before the same court.

Preliminary injunction ruling: After a May 19 hearing, the court denied the motion on June 3, holding the APA claims were non-justiciable because they challenged programmatic decisions rather than discrete actions.
Constitutional claims: The court found them deficient (statutory claims in disguise), concluded plaintiffs were unlikely to succeed on the merits, and denied the preliminary injunction.

Amended complaint (July 21): Narrowed to ten specific studies/datasets; alleges defendants’ cessation of access hindered use and was arbitrary and capricious under the APA; seeks dataset-specific injunctive relief.
Status: The case remains ongoing.
item_B: Plaintiffs (two non-profit educational research organizations, represented by NAACP LDF) filed suit on April 24, 2025 against the U.S. Department of Education and its Secretary.
The case challenges alleged actions to dismantle the Institute of Education Sciences (IES), the Department’s research arm.

Alleged factual basis: cancellation of over $900 million in research contracts, a Reduction in Force eliminating about 90% of IES staff, and restrictions on researchers’ access to critical educational data.
Legal basis asserted: APA violations (arbitrary and capricious; beyond ESRA authority) and a Separation of Powers claim; ESRA mandates IES’s data collection and dissemination work.
Relief sought: declaratory and injunctive orders reinstating contracts and staff, restoring data access, and halting efforts to incapacitate IES.
Case assignment: Judge Trevor N. McFadden.
Plaintiffs moved for a preliminary injunction to halt the challenged actions during litigation.
Defendants’ opposition: argued lack of jurisdiction and that staffing/funding decisions are committed to agency discretion and unreviewable.
Ruling on June 3, 2025: Preliminary injunction denied; court found the claims to be an improper APA programmatic challenge and dismissed the constitutional claim as repackaged statutory claims.
The denial opinion was issued jointly with a related case: Association for Education Finance and Policy, Inc. v. McMahon, No. 1:25-cv-00999.
Posture: Plaintiffs filed a First Amended Complaint on July 21, 2025; briefing set for the Department’s anticipated motion to dismiss.

item_A: The case involves a non-profit watchdog’s April 4, 2025 lawsuit against the CDC, HHS, and the agencies’ heads after the CDC eliminated its entire FOIA office on April 1, 2025 as part of a government-wide reduction in force; on the day of the closure, the plaintiff submitted five expedited FOIA requests about staff reductions and a reportedly suppressed CDC measles risk/vaccination assessment and received automated replies that the FOIA office was on administrative leave and could not respond. Supported by these events and responses, the suit was brought under FOIA and the APA, alleging an unlawful policy and practice of non-compliance and arbitrary and capricious agency action, with requested declaratory and injunctive relief to compel processing of the FOIA requests and reverse the office’s closure. Background includes assignment to Judge Timothy J. Kelly, denial of a preliminary injunction on June 4, 2025 due to lack of irreparable harm (records not time-sensitive and organizational harm not irreparable), filing of a First Amended Complaint on June 25, 2025, and the case’s ongoing posture with dispositive motions including the plaintiff’s motion for summary judgment.
item_B: On April 1, 2025, the CDC closed its FOIA office and did not comply with CREW’s subsequent requests for expedited FOIA processing.
CREW’s FOIA requests sought records about CDC staff reductions and other matters of significant public interest, including an ongoing national measles outbreak.

Background: HHS disbanded CDC’s FOIA office and put staff on administrative leave as part of a workforce reduction (from 82,000 to 62,000) under EO 14210, which directed agencies to prepare for large-scale RIFs.
CREW filed suit on April 4, 2025 in the U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia against the CDC, HHS, and the heads of those departments.
CREW, represented by in-house counsel, sought declaratory and injunctive relief under FOIA and the APA.

Allegations: Eliminating CDC’s FOIA office violated federal law and impeded access to critical records (including on measles outbreaks); defendants wrongfully denied expedited FOIA processing; maintained a policy or practice of FOIA violations; and took unlawful, arbitrary, and capricious action under the APA.
Relief sought: declaration that the actions are unlawful; injunction restoring FOIA operations; an order compelling expedited processing of CREW’s requests; and attorneys’ fees.
The case was assigned to Judge Timothy J. Kelly.
Procedural events: Plaintiffs moved for a preliminary injunction and partial summary judgment, arguing no disputed facts and seeking expedited resolution on FOIA and APA “contrary to law” claims.

Ruling: The court denied a preliminary injunction on June 4, holding CREW did not show irreparable harm; the court found the records would not imminently lose value and that harm to CREW’s organizational mission was not irreparable under FOIA.

Subsequent proceedings: The court set an expedited schedule; Plaintiffs filed an amended complaint (expanding FOIA noncompliance facts and noting CDC’s FOIA office is not fulfilling responsibilities) and dropped the APA arbitrary-and-capricious claim; Plaintiffs moved for summary judgment on FOIA policy/practice noncompliance and APA contrary-to-law claims.
Status: Ongoing.

item_A: FinCEN issued the Southwest Border GTO on March 11, 2025, mandating MSBs in 30 ZIP codes near the U.S.–Mexico border to report transfers to/from Mexico exceeding $200 per person, a threshold far below the $10,000 reporting standard elsewhere.

On May 30, 2025, Valuta Corporation, Inc. and Payan's Fuel Center, Inc. filed suit in the Western District of Texas against FinCEN (and Director Andrea Gacki), the Treasury (and its Secretary), and the U.S. Attorney General; they are represented by the Institute for Justice and seek injunctive and declaratory relief. Judge Leon Schydlower presides.
Plaintiffs challenge the GTO on Fourth Amendment, Administrative Procedure Act (lack of notice-and-comment), and Non-Delegation Doctrine grounds.

Plaintiffs sought a TRO on May 30, 2025, alleging irreparable business harms: massive increase in reporting (about 1,600 reports in a month vs. 123 in the prior year), higher labor costs, exposure to severe fines, and customer loss to competitors in untargeted ZIP codes.

The court granted a TRO on June 24, 2025 (extended to July 22), finding likely success on an APA arbitrary-and-capricious claim (failure to address evasion via untargeted ZIP codes and customer flight) and immediate irreparable harms (risk of closure, reputational injury, loss of customers/goodwill).
Plaintiffs sought class certification on July 2, 2025 for MSBs operating in the targeted ZIP codes and not already plaintiffs elsewhere.
On July 3, 2025, plaintiffs moved for summary judgment, Rule 65(a)(2) final judgment, and a preliminary injunction, seeking APA vacatur to nullify the GTO universally.
The court granted a preliminary injunction on July 22, 2025, prohibiting enforcement or implementation of the GTO.
Status: ongoing.
item_B: On May 30, 2025, two family-owned MSBs in El Paso, Texas, sued the U.S. Department of the Treasury, FinCEN, and their leaders.
The case was filed as a putative class action on behalf of other affected MSBs.
Plaintiffs are represented by the Institute for Justice.
The lawsuit challenges a FinCEN Geographic Targeting Order issued on March 14, 2025.
The GTO mandates CTR filings for cash transactions over $200 (down from the standard $10,000) for MSBs in 30 zip codes along the Texas and California U.S.-Mexico border.
FinCEN’s stated purpose for the GTO is to combat illicit financial activities by drug cartels.
Plaintiffs report massive compliance burdens, including one plaintiff filing about 1,600 CTRs in the first month versus 123 in the entire prior year.
Plaintiffs allege loss of revenue and customer goodwill due to customers moving to MSBs in non-targeted zip codes to avoid data collection.
Plaintiffs seek to vacate the GTO, have it declared unlawful, and permanently enjoin its enforcement.

Legal bases asserted include APA and constitutional claims: Fourth Amendment (general warrant), APA arbitrary and capricious (no reasoned explanation for $200 threshold or zip code selection), exceeding Bank Secrecy Act authority, failure to use notice-and-comment, and unlawful delegation.
The case was assigned to Judge Leon Schydlower.

Plaintiffs moved for a TRO; on June 24, 2025, the court granted it, finding a substantial likelihood of success on the arbitrary-and-capricious claim, and temporarily barred GTO enforcement against the named plaintiffs.
The TRO was extended on July 2, 2025.
A preliminary injunction was granted on July 22, 2025, and remains in effect.
A motion for class certification and a combined motion for summary judgment and a preliminary injunction are pending.
Related cases in W.D. Tex. and S.D. Cal. also challenge the GTO, and other federal judges have issued preliminary injunctions against it.

item_A: In April 2025, defendants abruptly terminated over 370 multi-year grants/cooperative agreements totaling more than $820 million across critical public safety and social service programs.
Five nonprofits filed a class action on May 21, 2025 in D.D.C. against the DOJ, the Attorney General, and OJP (and its acting head); the case was assigned to Judge Amit Mehta.
Plaintiffs immediately sought class certification and a preliminary injunction.
Requested relief included preliminary and permanent injunctions to halt and restore/preserve funding, declaratory relief under the APA, and attorneys’ fees and costs.
A coalition of 33 amici (including local governments) supported plaintiffs, underscoring the terminated grants’ critical public safety and victim-service functions.
Defendants characterized the dispute as routine contract administration, not a broad unlawful policy change.
Defendants moved to dismiss, arguing lack of jurisdiction, likely failure on the merits, and no irreparable harm.
Plaintiffs contended that even if direct payment could not be ordered, relief such as reinstating grants was available notwithstanding the cited Supreme Court decision.

After a June 26 hearing, the court dismissed the case on July 7 for lack of APA cause of action and jurisdiction, while noting the terminations were unfair and indiscriminate but beyond its remedial power.
Plaintiffs promptly appealed and sought injunctions pending appeal in both the district court and the D.C. Circuit.

Plaintiffs cited irreparable harms including specialized staff layoffs, program eliminations, and reputational damage, with specific impacts in King County (increased homicides after gang outreach layoffs), FORCE Detroit, HRiA, and Stop AAPI Hate.
The district court had recognized likely harm to vulnerable communities from the terminations.
Judicial characterizations of the terminations included “unquestionably arbitrary,” “shameful,” and “unfair and indiscriminate.”
The court acknowledged that the jurisdictional issue was far from obvious and contested within the Circuit.
Plaintiffs sought waiver of any injunction bond due to the financial strain from the funding cuts.
The district court denied an injunction pending appeal but entered a stipulated injunction barring re-obligation or diminishment of the terminated funds and waived any bond.
On August 1, 2025, the D.C. Circuit denied an injunction pending appeal for failure to substantiate irreparable harm.
The litigation remains ongoing in both the district court and the D.C. Circuit.
item_B: On May 21, 2025, five nonprofit organizations filed a class-action lawsuit against DOJ, OJP, the U.S. Attorney General, and the Acting Head of OJP, represented by private counsel and Democracy Forward Foundation.
In April 2025, OJP abruptly terminated 370+ multi-year grants and cooperative agreements, cutting over $820 million for public safety and community violence intervention programs nationwide.

Plaintiffs, who provide victim services, violence prevention, and law-enforcement training, received identical form emails terminating their awards under 2 C.F.R. § 200.340(a)(4) as no longer effectuating program goals, with DOJ citing a priority shift toward law enforcement operations, combating violent crime, and aiding trafficking/sexual-assault victims.
Plaintiffs sought declaratory and injunctive relief to vacate the terminations and restore funding for themselves and similarly situated grantees.

Plaintiffs alleged APA violations (arbitrary and capricious, contrary to law, abuse of discretion) and constitutional violations (Fifth Amendment due process—procedural and vagueness—separation of powers, and Spending/Appropriations Clauses).

The government moved to dismiss, asserting the terminations followed a multi-month, individualized review to align funding with current priorities and that the district court lacked jurisdiction under the Tucker Act because the dispute is fundamentally contractual and belongs in the Court of Federal Claims.

On July 7, 2025, Judge Amit P. Mehta dismissed the case, finding no district court jurisdiction over the APA claims because they are essentially contract claims barred by the Tucker Act (relying on Department of Education v. California), holding the constitutional claims failed on the merits, and denying preliminary injunction and class certification as moot, while describing the government’s actions as shameful and arbitrary in lay terms.

Plaintiffs appealed to the D.C. Circuit on July 8, 2025; on July 21, 2025, the district court partially granted an injunction pending appeal, barring re-obligation of the five named plaintiffs’ terminated funds until October 1, 2025, without reinstating the grants.
Documentary evidence includes identical termination emails and notices citing 2 C.F.R. § 200.340(a)(4) and explaining a DOJ priority shift.

item_A: The case challenges congressional action directed at Northwestern University.

Parties and filing: On April 9, 2025, two Northwestern clinical law professors sued the House Committee on Education and Workforce and its Chair and Subcommittee Chair, plus nominal defendants Northwestern University, its President, and the Chair of its Board of Trustees.

Background: Northwestern Law’s Bluhm Legal Clinic provides pro bono legal services across 20 programs; the plaintiffs are clinical professors affiliated with the Community Justice and Civil Rights Clinic and the Center on Negotiation, Mediation, and Restorative Justice.

Background events: In 2024, Northwestern reached an agreement with Gaza war protestors to remove an encampment in exchange for continued peaceful protests; that year, the House Committee made multiple information requests to Northwestern about the protests.
Context: Following Executive Order 14188 (Jan. 29, 2025) to combat antisemitism, DOJ formed a task force and opened investigations into Northwestern and four other universities.

Challenged congressional action: In March 2025, the House Committee demanded documents about Northwestern Law’s clinics—policies/guidance, Bluhm Legal Clinic budget, and hiring/performance reviews for one plaintiff—citing Northwestern’s free representation of anti-Israeli highway blockage organizers.

Plaintiffs’ constitutional claims: First Amendment (viewpoint discrimination; interference with advocacy), Fifth Amendment due process, Sixth Amendment right to counsel (third-party standing), and Fifth Amendment equal protection (animus based on political affiliations).
Requested relief: Declaratory and injunctive relief to declare the Committee’s demand unconstitutional and to bar Northwestern and its officials from producing responsive documents.
Assignment: The case is before Judge Elaine E. Bucklo.

Emergency TRO request (Apr. 9, 2025): Plaintiffs sought to stay the Committee’s demand to prevent compliance by Apr. 10, alleging a politically motivated, pretextual investigation and harm to Northwestern’s clinical programs.

Subsequent events: The Committee withdrew its request; on Apr. 10, 2025, the court denied the TRO without prejudice as moot; the case continues.
